HEADWORD: Surgery
<hw>Sur"ge*ry</hw> <pr>(s⟦ucir⟧r"j⟦etil⟧r*⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>surgenrie</ets>, <ets>surgerie</ets>; cf. OF.
<ets>cirurgie</ets>, F. <ets>chirurgie</ets>, L. <ets>chirurgia</ets>,
Gr. <?/. See <er>Surgeon</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art of
healing by manual operation; that branch of medical science which treats
of manual operations for the healing of diseases or injuries of the
body; that branch of medical science which has for its object the cure
of local injuries or diseases, as wounds or fractures, tumors, etc.,
whether by manual operation or by medicines and constitutional
treatment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A surgeon's operating room or laboratory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surgical</ent>⟦br⟧
